# ECS

## Core concepts

| Concept | Role | Lives in |
|---------|------|----------|
| **Entity** | Plain bag of components; no methods | Game `createXEntity()` factories |
| **Component** | Data-only plain object | `viberanium/components/` or game `components/` |
| **System** | `installXSystem(registry, ...deps)` — one concern per installer | `viberanium/src/systems/` or game `systems/` |
| **Scene** | Owns a scene `Registry`; load/unload level content | Game `scenes/` |
| **Game** | Owns persistent game `Registry` + active scene | `bootstrap.ts` |

## Entity assembly

Entities are built by game factories, then registered by the scene:

```typescript
const entity = registry.createBare();
entity.components[COMPONENT_KEYS.transform] = createTransform();
entity.components[COMPONENT_KEYS.character] = createCharacterController();
entity.components[COMPONENT_KEYS.movementIntent] = createMovementIntent();
entity.components[PLAYER_CONTROLLER_KEY] = createPlayerController();
registry.register(entity);
```

Mesh sub-entities use `createBare()` → attach components → `register(entity)`.

## Component rules

- Data only — no `actions`, no registry imports, no per-frame logic
- Use `COMPONENT_KEYS` constants — never raw string literals for component keys
- Controllers write `movementIntent`; shared systems read it
- **Movement** is the canonical term for anything that can move — use `movementIntent`, `movementBlend`, `movementAnimTime`; never `locomotion*`

## System rules

- One concern per `install*System` — never combine input + physics + animation
- Query the registry each frame — never hold entity references or collider arrays
- Install on the registry that owns the entities (scene registry for level content)

## Controller pattern

Player and AI characters share movement, physics, collision, and animation systems. Only the controller differs:

| Component | Written by | Read by |
|-----------|-----------|---------|
| `playerController` (sandbox) | — (tag) | `installPlayerInputSystem` |
| `robotAi` (sandbox) | — (data) | `installRobotAiSystem` |
| `movementIntent` | controller systems | `installMovementSystem` |
| `character` | movement + physics | physics, state, animation |
| `navGrid` | — (data, `dirty` flag) | `installNavGridSystem` (rebuild when dirty), `installRobotAiSystem` |

## Registry queries

```typescript
for (const e of registry.view(COMPONENT_KEYS.character)) { ... }

const colliders = registry.getComponentsByName(COMPONENT_KEYS.collider) as Collider[];
```

- `view(key)` — cached entity list for one component key
- `getComponentsByName(key)` — flat list of all component instances (collision, raycasts)
- Never pass collider arrays or entity references to system installers

## Component lifecycle

```typescript
registry.addComponent(entity, COMPONENT_KEYS.collider, collider);
registry.removeComponent(entity, COMPONENT_KEYS.collider);
registry.deregister(entity.id);
```

`addComponent` / `removeComponent` invalidate the view cache for that key.

## Scene boundaries

- **Game registry** — persistent entities (render pipeline draw action, scene manager, global input handlers)
- **Scene registry** — ephemeral; one per active level visit
- `scene.load()` creates all level content including the nav grid entity
- `scene.unload()` deregisters **all** entities and clears ground — nothing persists on the registry
- `game.setActiveScene(null)` drops the active scene; the `Scene` object is discarded after `switchTo` completes
- Frame loop runs game registry actions first, then active scene registry actions

## Nav grid

The nav grid is a first-class scene component — not a hidden cache inside an AI system.

| Piece | Location | Role |
|-------|----------|------|
| `NavGridComponent` | `viberanium/components/navGrid.ts` | Grid bounds, `blocked` cells, `agentRadius`, `dirty` flag |
| `createNavGrid()` | component factory | Allocates grid data; `dirty` starts `true` |
| `markNavGridDirty(registry)` | component helper | Sets `dirty = true` after collider changes during an active level |
| `updateNavGridBlocked()` | `viberanium/navigation/navGrid.ts` | Pure rebuild of `blocked` from static colliders |
| `installNavGridSystem()` | `viberanium/systems/navGridSystem.ts` | Rebuilds only when `dirty`; clears flag after rebuild |
| `findPath` / `pickRandomObjective` | `viberanium/navigation/astar.ts` | Read the grid; never build or own one |

### Lifecycle

Nav grid entity is registered in `scene.load()` and deregistered in `scene.unload()` alongside props and NPCs. Only the active level holds a grid in memory.

```typescript
// inside scene.load()
const navGridEntity = registry.createBare();
navGridEntity.components[COMPONENT_KEYS.navGrid] = createNavGrid(navGridConfig);
registry.register(navGridEntity);
```

Bounds come from `LevelDefinition.navGrid` in the level catalog.

### Dirty rebuild contract

- **Do not** rebuild the nav grid every update — only when `navGrid.dirty` is true
- **Do** call `markNavGridDirty(registry)` when static colliders are added or removed during an active level (e.g. `instantiateStaticProp`, runtime destructibles)
- AI systems read the scene grid via `registry.view(COMPONENT_KEYS.navGrid)` — never build or cache their own grid

## Forbidden

- Monolithic systems combining input, physics, and animation
- `registry.view('character')[0]` in bootstrap to wire a specific entity
- Bootstrap-time `staticColliders: Collider[]` arrays passed to systems
- Behavior logic inside component factories
- Per-frame nav grid rebuilds without `dirty`
- AI-owned nav grid caches (`WeakMap<Registry, NavGrid>`) — the scene component is the single source of truth
- Persistent nav grid entities across `unload()` — grid is level content, destroyed with the level
- `locomotion*` naming for movement-related components or fields — use `movement*`
